Tool Selection and Design Process :
For this task, I chose to use Canva because of its extensive library of educational templates and intuitive drag-and-drop interface. My goal was to create a clean, one-page visual resource that balanced informative text with engaging icons to ensure my batchmates could quickly grasp the core concepts of digital literacy.

Infographic Content :
The design is divided into three primary sections:

What is Digital Literacy?: I defined it not just as technical skill, but as the ability to find, evaluate, and communicate information clearly through various digital platforms.

Safe Internet Practices: This section highligts the "Think Before You Click" mantra, emphasizing the importance of two-factor authentication and identifying phishing attempts.

Email Etiquette: I included a checklist for professional communication, such as using clear subject lines, maintaining a formal tone, and proofreading before sending.

Reflections
One thing I found particularly interesting while creating this infographic was how challenging it is to simplify complex security concepts into short, punchy bullet points. I initially had too much text, but I learned that in digital design, "less is more." The most difficult part was selecting a color palette that was professional yet eye-catching enough to stand out in a busy student repository.
